text: Read the original book Wonder by Raquel J. Palacio. I remember reading and voting for it at the London Carnegie book awards and it was really heartwarming. The author Palacio, stated that the inspiration came from when her daughter had seen a disabled child and began to cry and as she tried to discreetly move her child away from them, which only made the situation worse. She said she couldn't forget the way the Mother looked at her. Inspiring to write a book about such a young child's struggles in a materialistic world is beautiful.

text: I have been waiting for this movie for YEARS. I remember the first time reading the book and feeling amazing. My brother is disabled and looks quite similar to August (Auggie) and me reading a book about the life of someone with a disability and about the family and his sister dealing with it I FELT OUT OF THIS WORLD. For the words in the book to be transported into a movie and for the words to come alive just makes me realise I wouldn't swap my brother for the world. My brother was born with Golden Har syndrome but to me he doesn't look any different from normal person because he IS a normal person; he may not look like one but on the inside he is the most amazing, bubbly and kindest person I know. Wonder put all of my thoughts and feelings and probably my brother's as well onto a page.

text: I know what your thinking. This film is going to be great. It will be about a boy who has to cope with looking different and then people will accept him because he is actually a genius. But on the inside this is one of the most generic films this year. You have heard the same narrative before in things like diary of a wimpy kid and middle school the worst years of my life and while this film will most likely execute the trope better, it is still the same trope. Secondly the main character does not need to be disfigured to suit the role you could just as easily had an average person and the story would not change. Remember no matter how much creativity is put into a work, while it does deserve some credit it is still a company. The only reason the main character is disfigured is to pull at your heartstrings and provides nothing but a unnecessary conflict at the start of the movie and then becomes the typical movie I was talking about earlier. Also the other reason they use this in particular is because it is based off a book. They want you to think things like "oh I read that in 6th grade, so maybe I'll watch the movie that the book has produced" when really a. If something has to play off nostalgia it may be compensating for something missing and b. If you read this book in 6th grade it might be aimed and suited for a younger audience and not have a complex enough plot line for adults and teenagers to enjoy. I am not saying that this WILL be a bad or even mediocre film I am just saying it has got the hallmarks of one.

text: This looks like such a great movie; However, I am a pediatric audiologist, and I have to ask: where is this child's Baha? A Baha (AKA bone anchored hearing aid) is a special hearing device for individuals who have hearing loss secondary to external/middle ear abnormalities. This child appears to have atresia/microtia: small/malformed ears with absent or small ear canals. With this type of presentation, I would expect this kiddo to have a substantial hearing loss that would have a severe impact on the development of speech/language and general communication, but it can be easily remedied with a special type of hearing aid. While this movie is doing GREAT things to bring awareness to his condition, I sincerely hope that they bring awareness to the importance of hearing aid as well. Most of my patients are ashamed to wear any type of hearing aid because, let be honest, school-aged children are brutal. Demystifying a hearing aid by portraying it in popular movies/media has the potential to make a world of difference in these children's life. I am crossing my fingers that the movie, even briefly, touches on this topic!

text: Everyone needs to see this movie! It doesn't matter if you're 2, 102, or anywhere in between. I promise this movie will make a difference in your life. Flash back 5 years to my 4th grade year. I was sitting on the floor with my best friend and 20 other kids surrounding my teacher as she captivated our attention in the reading of this book. Now to my 5th grade year. Both me and my best friend got the book and 365 Days of Wonder for Christmas. We read that book over and over again. We even read a quote a day all year starting on Janruary 1st. Next my 6th grade year. I wrote an essay about Wonder, which was the 3rd school project I had done on it. My teacher wrote a comment on my writing that it made her cry. Seventh grade next. I did a series of 5 mini projects with it. My teacher was so amazed with what I was able to do with that assignment. Now 8th grade. My best friend and I went with our moms to meet the author. We listened to R.J Palacio talk about her reasoning behind writing the book, then we met her and she signed our books. Now here I am, my freshman year of high school. I have read the book 16 times and completed 5 projects (all As I might add) on Wonder. The day the movie premiered, I was sitting in a theatre next to my best friend. text: This movie really hits home, with all my clothes on I look like a normal person, but if ever I go to the beach, people literally walk away in fear. Because with colon cancer and Crohnâ€™s disease Iâ€™ve had 33 operations on my abdomen and chest, my entire upper torso is horribly scarred, from numerous infections and so many operations. It doesnâ€™t bother me in the least, Iâ€™ve beaten cancer three times already, and I look at them is battle scars, reminder of the strength it took to beat this horrible disease, but other people see me and literally turn away in disgust. I wonâ€™t even begin to tell you the horrible things people said to me, especially since my small bell now protrudes through my abdomen, and I need to use a catheter to empty my intestine through that towel a.k.a. stoma, eight times a day at least. But again Iâ€™m lucky that I can cover it up with a T-shirt, wearing your scars on your face for all the world to see must be the most challenging thing anybody could ever face, I have several friends that, for various medical reasons, have severe facial deformities, and I know the hell that theyâ€™ve gone through, and how cruel people can be. Absolutely boggles my mind how anybody could be so cruel and evil to judge and harass people based on something that is totally beyond their control. I always say thereâ€™s a special hell for people that cruel, because the people that I know with the so-called deformities, are the strongest most remarkable loving people Iâ€™ve ever met my life, and I donâ€™t see any deformity whatsoever, I see courage and strength, and beauty in their own unique way. The worst thing you can do to somebody who doesnâ€™t look like everyone else is to stare at them, trust me, I know how it feels, if youâ€™re curious, then by all means, please ask politely, and Iâ€™m very happy to explain it, but when people come up to you and say things like â€œoh my god what happened to you, that doesnâ€™t look normal!!!â€ (Iâ€™ve heard that one more times than I can count), are usually respond with â€œwhat happened to you?, Did your parents drop you on your head when you were just the child? â€œ. Iâ€™ve learned to grow thick skin as most people who stand out from the crowd do, at first it hurts, but after a while I just got angry, and begin telling people off, and now I could give a shit, because itâ€™s my life to live not theirs, nobody has the right to judge me except God himself! Getting back to this movie, if it is good as the preview seems, two things are going to happen, first, I guarantee you I will start bawling my eyes out, because it will bring back so many memories for myself, and for those friends of mine who suffered so much, and secondly, Iâ€™ll be bursting with pride for the character, and for the people I know, for their incredible current and strength, but also to honour The often downright cruel struggles they face on a daily basis growing up, and even as an adult it doesnâ€™t get much better. The world needs to learn compassion and love, we need to look past exterior appearances, and get to know the person inside. Because Iâ€™ve met a lot of beautiful people are just rotten inside, I donâ€™t care how good-looking you are, if youâ€™re arrogant youâ€™re the ugliest person in the world to me, I care whatâ€™s on the inside, and Iâ€™m not saying that because Iâ€™m ugly, are used to be a model in my early 20s, so Iâ€™m not ugly, far from it, the only difference being after 3 battles with colon cancer, my hair never grew back, so now Iâ€™m bald as a bowling ball, but so much stronger from the experience! The only thing I big all of you, please, if you see somebody who has any type of deformity, for God sake do not stare at them, you have no idea how horrible it makes them feel, if you want to know anything like I said just ask politely, some people may be a little offended, but in my experience most of us are quite glad to give you an explanation if youâ€™re polite about it.I understand itâ€™s human nature to look at the things that we donâ€™t understand or find out of place, itâ€™s an instinctual thing to do, but itâ€™s up to you as to how you go about it, because you can either make a persons day, or make them feel like a piece of shit, what type of person are you?

text: I think this is awesome because let's face it- we are have been 'freaks' at some point of our lives. Maybe you're the new kid in school. Maybe you need help breathing. My first best friend had asthma. We all have felt conflicted and lost and that doesn't give us the right to make others feel that way. When I was 7 years old, I moved to a totally different country that spoke a different language. The kids in my school-made fun of my name for 4 solid years because it was foreign and they couldn't pronounce it very well. I grew up shy, not being able to speak up for myself. Now, I'm 18, back in my home country and English skills have become an asset to me. We are all victims and survivors. I hope people learn from this movie.

text: I just stumbled upon this movie on cable tv and I loved it. I started reminiscing about my elementary years. My highschool had ups and down then I just finished college recently. I realized if I were to repeat a time of my life, I think it would have been my elementary from 4th to 5th grade. I think those were one of my best years although I hardly can recall all the memories. I remember having some really good friends back then but sadly lost touch with them especially since they moved away after graduation. If I were given a chance, I'd love to relive those years. It was a great time of friendship, innocence and just a happy life overall.
